INSERT INTO public.questions (exam_id, subject_id, year, paper, question_text, option_1, option_2, option_3, option_4, correct_option, explanation, difficulty) VALUES
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','e7eaeaa0-d839-4490-abed-c71027b61424',2023,'Paper-II','As per IS 456:2000, the minimum eccentricity for a RCC rectangular column of size 300×300mm, unsupported length 3.3m is:','10 mm','6.6 mm','16.6 mm','20 mm',4,'Minimum eccentricity = max(L/500, 20mm) = max(3300/500=6.6, 20) = 20mm. Also the code specifies emin ≥ 20mm for columns.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','e7eaeaa0-d839-4490-abed-c71027b61424',2023,'Paper-II','Consider the following pairs with respect to members of a steel roof truss. P. Principal tie: Top chord compression. Q. Sling: Main inclined members tension. R. Principal rafter: Lower chord tension. S. Strut: Compression.','P and R only','Q and S only','P, R and S only','R only',2,'P is incorrect: Principal rafter is top chord (compression), not principal tie. Q is correct: slings are tension members. R is incorrect: Principal tie is the lower chord (tension), not principal rafter. S is correct: struts are compression members. So Q and S only.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','e7eaeaa0-d839-4490-abed-c71027b61424',2023,'Paper-II','The following statements pertain to steel compression members. P. Slenderness ratio measures tendency to buckle. Q. Longer member for same cross-section has smaller tendency to buckle.','P only','Q only','Both P and Q','Neither P nor Q',1,'P is correct: slenderness ratio measures buckling tendency. Q is incorrect: longer members have greater tendency to buckle (more slender).','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','e7eaeaa0-d839-4490-abed-c71027b61424',2023,'Paper-II','The following statements pertain to steel beam design. P. Laterally unsupported beam governed by lateral torsional buckling. Q. Web crippling occurs due to excessive bending moment. R. Design bending strength governed by yield stress when adequately supported.','P only','Q only','P and R only','P, Q, R',3,'P is correct: lateral torsional buckling governs unsupported beams. Q is incorrect: web crippling occurs due to concentrated loads (bearing), not bending moment. R is correct: when adequately supported, yield stress governs.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','e7eaeaa0-d839-4490-abed-c71027b61424',2023,'Paper-II','According to IS 800:2007, partial safety factor for Dead load under Limit state of Strength (DL+LL+CL) is:','1.5','1.0','1.2','0.9',1,'IS 800:2007, for limit state of strength, the partial safety factor for dead load (DL) in combination DL+LL+CL is 1.5.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','e7eaeaa0-d839-4490-abed-c71027b61424',2023,'Paper-II','According to IS 800:2007, the recommended values of physical properties of structural steel are:','ρ=785, E=2000, μ=0.25','ρ=9850, E=2×10⁶, μ=0.4','ρ=6850, E=2×10⁴, μ=0.2','ρ=7850, E=2×10⁵, μ=0.3',4,'IS 800 specifies: Unit mass ρ = 7850 kg/m³, Modulus of Elasticity E = 2×10⁵ MPa, Poisson''s ratio μ = 0.3.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','e7eaeaa0-d839-4490-abed-c71027b61424',2023,'Paper-II','A steel built up column is subjected to an axial force of 3000 kN. The lacing system has to be designed for resisting a transverse shear of:','30 kN','45 kN','75 kN','150 kN',3,'Transverse shear in lacing = 2.5% of axial load = 0.025 × 3000 = 75 kN.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','e7eaeaa0-d839-4490-abed-c71027b61424',2023,'Paper-II','When fillet welds are subjected to normal stress σ and shear stress τ, the equivalent stress on the weld is computed as:','√(σ² + τ²)','√(3σ² + τ²)','√(σ² + 3τ²)','√(0.5σ² + 3τ²)',3,'As per IS 800, the equivalent stress for fillet welds subjected to combined normal and shear stress is √(σ² + 3τ²).','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','64289b52-861b-4a49-9286-4c4196691af7',2023,'Paper-II','In canal irrigation, the duty values at different points: DM (main canal), DD (distributary), DW (water course), DF (field). Arrange in decreasing order.','DM-DW-DD-DF','DF-DW-DD-DM','DF-DD-DW-DM','DM-DD-DW-DF',3,'Duty decreases as we move from field to source due to losses. Field has the highest duty (area actually irrigated), then water course, then distributary, then main canal (lowest due to conveyance losses). So DF > DD > DW > DM. Thus DF-DD-DW-DM.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','64289b52-861b-4a49-9286-4c4196691af7',2023,'Paper-II','Consider the following pairs with respect to diversion head works. P. Weir: heading up by gates. Q. Barrage: solid obstruction. R. Divide wall: at right angle to weir axis. S. Fish ladder: parallel to weir axis.','P and Q only','Q and S only','P, R and S only','R only',4,'P is incorrect: Weir is a solid obstruction, not gated. Q is incorrect: Barrage is gated, not solid obstruction. R is correct: Divide wall is at right angle to weir axis. S is incorrect: Fish ladder is not parallel to weir axis; it''s a structure to help fish migrate. So only R is correct.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','64289b52-861b-4a49-9286-4c4196691af7',2023,'Paper-II','Due to a storm, direct runoff occurs from a basin. The components of direct runoff are:','Surface runoff, prompt interflow and channel precipitation','Surface runoff and channel precipitation','Surface runoff, delayed interflow and base flow','Surface runoff and infiltration',1,'Direct runoff consists of surface runoff, prompt interflow (sub-surface flow that reaches the channel quickly), and channel precipitation. Base flow and delayed interflow are not part of direct runoff.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','64289b52-861b-4a49-9286-4c4196691af7',2023,'Paper-II','In irrigation practices, the water required to bring soil moisture to field capacity is:','Saturation capacity','Field capacity','Wilting point','Hygroscopic capacity',2,'Field moisture deficiency (also called soil moisture deficit) is the water required to bring the soil moisture content to field capacity.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','64289b52-861b-4a49-9286-4c4196691af7',2023,'Paper-II','The following details pertain to crossing of a canal and a natural drain. Bed level of Canal = +111m, FSD = 1.8m, Bed level of Drain = +109.4m, HFL depth = 2.2m. Suitable type of Cross drainage work is:','Aqueduct','Super Passage','Canal syphon','Syphon Aqueduct',4,'Canal bed level (+111m) is higher than drain bed (+109.4m). Canal FSL = 111+1.8 = 112.8m. Drain HFL = 109.4+2.2 = 111.6m. Since canal is higher and water has to flow above the drain, but the difference is small. Actually, the key says Syphon Aqueduct. This is when the canal is above the drain but the drain HFL is below the canal bed, requiring the canal water to be carried in a syphon.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','The following statements pertain to intakes/transportation of water. P. Weir intake is type of Canal intake. Q. Pipe intake is a type of River intake. R. Gravity conduits follow natural hydraulic gradient.','P and Q only','Q and R only','P and R only','R only',2,'P is incorrect: Weir intake is a river intake type. Q is correct: Pipe intake is a river intake. R is correct: Gravity conduits are designed to follow the natural hydraulic gradient.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','The water treatment units: P. Post chlorination, Q. Demineralization, R. Rapid sand filtration, S. Softening. Arrange in chronological order.','P-R-Q-S','R-P-Q-S','S-R-Q-P','R-S-P-Q',4,'The correct sequence: Rapid sand filtration (R) → Softening (S) → Demineralization (Q) → Post chlorination (P). Treatment follows: coagulation, sedimentation, filtration, softening, demineralization, disinfection.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','Which is the most acceptable economical option for solid waste management?','Composting','Pyrolysis','Incineration','Landfill',4,'Landfill is the most economical option for solid waste management in India, especially when considering capital and operational costs.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','A conventional rapid mixing tank treating water at 144 Million litres/day. If HRT is 72 seconds, the tank volume will be:','72 m³','120 m³','100 m³','10 m³',2,'Volume = Flow × Retention time. Flow = 144 MLD = 144,000 m³/day = 1.667 m³/s. HRT = 72s. Volume = 1.667 × 72 = 120 m³.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','The following statements pertain to air pollutants. P. Secondary pollutants produced by interaction of primary pollutants. Q. PAN is a secondary pollutant.','P only','Q only','Both P and Q','Neither P nor Q',3,'Both statements are correct: secondary pollutants are formed by interaction of primary pollutants, and PAN (Peroxy Acetyl Nitrate) is a secondary pollutant.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','Match the purpose served by valve with name. P. Stop and regulate flow Q. Drain line sections R. Prevent reversal of flow S. Keep pressure below specified value','P-3,Q-4,R-2,S-1','P-3,Q-2,R-4,S-1','P-2,Q-3,R-1,S-4','P-4,Q-3,R-2,S-1',1,'P: Line valve (3). Q: Scour valve (4) - drains sections. R: Check valve (2) - prevents reversal. S: Pressure relief valve (1) - keeps pressure below specified value.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','The treatments in a conventional sewage treatment plant: 1. Primary sedimentation, 2. Screening, 3. Trickling filter, 4. Grit chamber, 5. Disinfection, 6. Secondary sedimentation. Sequential order:','2-1-4-3-5-6','4-1-2-3-6-5','4-2-1-3-5-6','2-4-1-3-6-5',4,'The correct sequence: Screening (2) → Grit chamber (4) → Primary sedimentation (1) → Trickling filter (3) → Secondary sedimentation (6) → Disinfection (5). So 2-4-1-3-6-5.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','From a sewage pumping station, 2.5ml of raw sewage diluted to 250ml. Initial DO = 12mg/l, Final DO = 5mg/l. What is the BOD of raw sewage?','1200 mg/l','700 mg/l','240 mg/l','500 mg/l',2,'BOD = (DOᵢ - DOf) × (Dilution factor) = (12-5) × (250/2.5) = 7 × 100 = 700 mg/l.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','As per CPHEEO guidelines, the peak factor for per capita sewage flow:','Always a constant value','High values for high population','High values for low population','Low values for low population',3,'Peak factor is high for low population (due to higher variability) and low for high population (more uniform flow).','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c542f294-548d-4129-8d45-b3f75629dc1b',2023,'Paper-II','For sewage treatment using an oxidation pond, when overloaded, which chemical is added to stimulate algal growth?','Sodium nitrate','Sodium chloride','Calcium hydroxide','Bleaching powder',1,'Sodium nitrate is a nitrogen source that stimulates algal growth. Chlorides and calcium hydroxide are not used for this purpose, and bleaching powder is a disinfectant.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','637bf719-8dde-4035-946c-4242372328e2',2023,'Paper-II','Consider the types of road surface: B. Thin Bituminous, E. Earth, G. Gravel, C. Cement concrete. Ascending order of steepness of camber (low to high):','E - G - B - C','B - C - E - G','G - C - B - E','C - B - G - E',4,'Camber values: Cement concrete (lowest: 1.0-2.0%) < Thin Bituminous (2.0-2.5%) < Gravel (2.5-3.0%) < Earth (3.0-4.0%). So C, B, G, E.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','637bf719-8dde-4035-946c-4242372328e2',2023,'Paper-II','Consider the following pairs with respect to traffic regulation. P. Rotary island: Traffic control structure. Q. Traffic studies: Flow characteristics. R. Speed limit sign: Informatory sign. S. Clover leaf interchange: Grade separation.','P and Q only','R and S only','P, Q and S only','R only',3,'P is correct: rotary island is a traffic control structure. Q is correct: traffic studies analyze flow characteristics. R is incorrect: speed limit sign is a regulatory sign, not informatory. S is correct: cloverleaf is a grade-separated interchange.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','637bf719-8dde-4035-946c-4242372328e2',2023,'Paper-II','The following statements pertain to pavement design. P. Westergaard''s method for flexible pavements. Q. CBR method for concrete pavements.','P only','Q only','Both P and Q','Neither P nor Q',4,'P is incorrect: Westergaard''s method is used for rigid (concrete) pavements. Q is incorrect: CBR method is used for flexible pavements, not concrete. So neither is correct.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','637bf719-8dde-4035-946c-4242372328e2',2023,'Paper-II','In a horizontal circular highway curve, for constant coefficient of lateral friction, the required super elevation:','Increases with increase in speed and decrease in radius','Increases with decrease in both speed and radius','Increases with increase in both speed and radius','Decreases with increase in speed and decrease in radius',1,'Super elevation e = V²/(gR). So e increases with increase in V and decreases with increase in R. Thus e increases with increase in speed and decrease in radius.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','637bf719-8dde-4035-946c-4242372328e2',2023,'Paper-II','In a highway an ascending gradient of 1 in 50 meets another ascending gradient of 1 in 30, determine the deviation angle?','55','75','330','75',2,'Deviation angle = |n₁ - n₂| = |(1/50) - (1/30)| = |30-50|/1500 = 20/1500 = 1/75 = 0.01333 rad. The angle in minutes = (1/75) × (180/π) × 60 ≈ 45.8 minutes. But the options are in seconds maybe? Let me check: n = 1/50 - 1/30 = 1/75. In degrees = 0.01333 × 180/π = 0.763°. In minutes = 0.763 × 60 = 45.8′. The options show 55, 75, 330, 75 - they might be in seconds? Actually the key says option 2 (75). The deviation angle formula gives the result in ° or minutes? The options seem to be in minutes or seconds. I''ll trust the key.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','637bf719-8dde-4035-946c-4242372328e2',2023,'Paper-II','As per IRC 73-1980, the width of carriage way for non-urban highway two lane road with raised kerbs:','7 m','8 m','7.5 m','6.5 m',3,'IRC 73 specifies carriageway width for two-lane roads with raised kerbs as 7.5m (3.75m per lane).','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c39bc91d-4a88-42c6-b1f7-ae4fc2b0dba1',2023,'Paper-II','The following statements are given: P. Consolidation is a function of total stress. Q. During compaction soil is completely saturated. R. In consolidation, volume reduction is due to expulsion of pore water. S. Compaction is instantaneous.','P and Q only','R and S only','P, Q and R only','P, Q and S only',2,'P is incorrect: consolidation is a function of effective stress, not total stress. Q is incorrect: compaction is done at optimum moisture content, not completely saturated. R is correct: consolidation involves expulsion of pore water. S is correct: compaction is almost instantaneous. So R and S only.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c39bc91d-4a88-42c6-b1f7-ae4fc2b0dba1',2023,'Paper-II','Match the Test/Equipment with Purpose. P. Hydrometer Q. Ring and Water replacement R. Sand bath method S. Casagrande''s apparatus','P-4,Q-3,R-1,S-2','P-3,Q-4,R-2,S-1','P-2,Q-3,R-1,S-4','P-4,Q-1,R-2,S-3',2,'Hydrometer: Grain size distribution (P-3). Ring and Water replacement: In-place density (Q-4). Sand bath method: Moisture content (R-2). Casagrande''s apparatus: Consistency limits (S-1).','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c39bc91d-4a88-42c6-b1f7-ae4fc2b0dba1',2023,'Paper-II','What is the correct sequence of Atterberg limits when moisture content is reduced from a large value: Liquid limit (LL), Plastic limit (PL), Shrinkage limit (SL)','SL, PL, LL','LL, SL, PL','PL, SL, LL','LL, PL, SL',4,'As moisture content decreases: Liquid limit (LL) → Plastic limit (PL) → Shrinkage limit (SL). So LL, PL, SL.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c39bc91d-4a88-42c6-b1f7-ae4fc2b0dba1',2023,'Paper-II','The saturated unit weight of a soil sample is 20.64 kN/m³. If unit weight of water is 10 kN/m³, estimate the submerged unit weight.','10.64','20.64','30.64','2.064',1,'Submerged unit weight = Saturated unit weight - Unit weight of water = 20.64 - 10 = 10.64 kN/m³.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c39bc91d-4a88-42c6-b1f7-ae4fc2b0dba1',2023,'Paper-II','The following statements pertain to a soil mass. P. High dry unit weight indicates more compact soil. Q. At liquid limit, liquidity index is zero.','P only','Q only','Both P and Q','Neither P nor Q',1,'P is correct: higher dry density means more compacted soil. Q is incorrect: liquidity index = (w - PL)/(LL - PL). At liquid limit, w = LL, so LI = 1. At plastic limit, LI = 0. So Q is false.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c39bc91d-4a88-42c6-b1f7-ae4fc2b0dba1',2023,'Paper-II','If qᵤ is the ultimate bearing capacity, then the net safe bearing capacity qₙₛ is given by:','(qᵤ - γD_f)/F','(qᵤ + γD_f)/F','qᵤ - γD_f/F','qᵤ + γD_f/F',1,'Net ultimate bearing capacity = qᵤ - γD_f (overburden pressure). Net safe bearing capacity = (qᵤ - γD_f)/F.','medium'),
('e33338c9-740c-48c4-914b-2cca3e9c1668','c39bc91d-4a88-42c6-b1f7-ae4fc2b0dba1',2023,'Paper-II','As per IS classification, Fine sand particle size ranges from:','4.75 mm to 20 mm','4.75 mm to 2 mm','2 mm to 0.425 mm','0.425 mm to 0.075 mm',4,'IS classification: Fine sand: 0.425 mm to 0.075 mm. Medium sand: 0.425-2 mm. Coarse sand: 2-4.75 mm. Gravel: 4.75-80 mm.','medium');